segments.text: And people around there, I'm sure that there were people in there that, there were students in there, boys, that had nothing at all.
And they got jobs.
You could get a job with families.
They needed help.
Students would come and work with them or something like that.
And, of course, they worked all across the campus.
Yeah, and student labor was common, very common.
You had the professors and some of the personnel paid, but other than that, it was always student labor.
And you got 25 cents an hour.
Now, when did you start doing chores for pay?
Right away.
I laid 6,000 feet of six-inch cast iron water mains in College Park.
I had a hundred niggers working for me.
My, my, my.
How old were you then, probably?
High school?
No.
High school, I was in grade school.
My, my, my.
I was a young kid.
I was just a kid.
Now, your dad was a part of the group.
Yeah, the college park was founded by Dan Scholes.
uh, Dr., uh, uh, well, let's see, Dan Scrooge, and then there was, uh, when he was in the economics, Dr. Clark.
He was a crazy man.
He was odd.
Uh, he was in the economics department, and his idea was that, uh,
On an automobile, when your repair bills got beyond what it cost to get a new one, your payments on a new one, you traded it off.
You always drove an ethics car.
Now, of the partners in the Southside, who put in the biggest investment?
Who put the most money into it, do you know?
I don't know.
Or did they do it equally?
They must have done it equally with the addition of the bank.
I don't think there was any money put in it.
Which bank underwrote it?
I think at that time it must have been the First State and Trust Fund.
Okay, from downtown Bryan.
And about how many acres of land did they develop?
It's about a hundred.
And who'd they get the land, who'd they buy it from?
Hard liquor.
And it was called the Southside Development Company.
The man that, okay, let's count them all.
There was Burchard.
house is still on Dexter.
He took care of all the books.
He was a, he worked for the state.
You were saying Burchard?
Burchard.
The same one who worked for FAPS.
He was a state chemist of some sort.
And so they were there and they kept good books on the thing.
Then there was a

a fellow named Doherty and he just had one house there and then there was Lancaster well that was their father and their grandfather their grandfather was the one that I had contact with he taught me he was an old carpenter and he years and years many hours I spent in there he was showing me how to
to handle tools and carpentry.
And then there was Dr. Clark, and there was Dad.
That was the whole thing of it.
And that's 1920?
That's what surprised me.
I was looking at it not too long ago, and it surprised me.
I thought it was later than that.
And what they did, right down Dexter,
You can just see them.
Each of them was granted two lots.
And the first one is Butchard.
The next one is Dougherty.
And the next one is Lancaster.
And then Dad said, and Dr.
Then it was Dr. Clark.
He said, I want one lot here, but I want one lot down here.
And Dad said, I want both of my lots together.
Because when I meet my wife, I don't want nobody to know about it.
So that was the setup.
And I think they just gave those lots to him.
Now, the land went along Jersey from Dexter to what street?
What were the boundaries?
The boundary on the east side is where the church is now.
Where the Episcopal Church?
Yeah.
They're in South.
Some of that property is in South.
Some of it is in College Park and some of it is in Southoverwood.
And then on the west side is up there where the Former Students Association is.
That's the west end of it.
And it went straight back and they had

originally it had a the south corner the south corner down there had the lots were laid out for niggers there were niggers now were there any houses east of Southside Park no not for a long time that's what I thought but people came in Herschel Burgess bought it from
Shoots.
Shoots, I think.
And then he developed it?
He developed it.
He and his wife developed that.
And that's what's called South Oakwood.
That's the home of the United States.
I was asking their son.
I know him.
He was in the American Legion when we were together.
And...
I knew him not too well, but there was a group of them.
They had a whole family down there, but they moved off somewhere else, and Schubert told me that they had a place over north of my place.
Now, the son is still alive.
He was in World War II.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
He was the one I was telling you got his arm hurt.
Now did, when those new houses were built over there, did that change the life of this faculty family?
Oh yeah.
Oh yeah.
But you still came on the campus to play with your buddies?
Not really.
Really?
So you played... By that time I was going to school.
Oh, okay.
At that time, I was going to college or going to Bryan High School.
All right.
Now, when you went down to Bryan, somebody took you down there in a car?
No, I drove.
Oh, you drove.
All right.
28 Hub Mobile.
28 Hub Mobile.
All right.
Okay.
It was a sedan.
Big old six-cylinder.
Okay.
And did anybody ride with you?
About how many college kids went down to Bryan?
So you were kind of by yourself?
Did they tease you or anything about?
No.
I was so interested in the shop work they had.
that it didn't really bother me because, oh, I made a lot of friends, old John M. Barron and the Barron's and his sister, the big old gal.
Let's see, now the Brogdon girls, they're older than you are, Daisy and Eileen?
Daisy worked for Dad.
Okay.
He came in after the Martins, see,
We brought this other family with us when we came here, the Martin family, and she was dad's secretary.
I see.
And she had brought, that's an interesting story, because she must have come from south Mississippi.
She met this English woman down in,

ground and guff for it someplace and they married him but he couldn't read or write and she taught him to read and write and then the next thing she did she brought him to Starkville because at that time I don't know that an A&M had ever happened but in Mississippi it did happen they had sort of a
lower grade school in the college.
A demonstration school.
No, it was just a regular old school.
Well, but I mean it was a school for some of their education majors to get experience teaching and all?
No, I don't think so.
It was just playing.
They knew they had to
educate those people, and the college was appointed to do it.
Oh, I see, okay.
And so that's what, that's what, it was just straight, straight out.
And so he got John Martin, Johnny, Johnny Martin, he got, he got his
I think he was up, he was in college by the time we moved over here.
But anyways, he and his wife and they had a little boy named John, too.
And they came in that big old hub mobile that Daddy bought.
And they lived in a building that's just south, north of the chemistry lab.

building in there, I don't know what it was used for, but they broke it up into little apartments, and they lived in that, and she worked for Dad, and he built a barn in College Park before we built the house, and he was an Englishman.
He would talk just like that, and so when
When Dad went to Europe, he instructed Dad how to handle the people in buying stuff over there.
And so then Dad brought back two or three
During those years, who were your closest buddies in high school?
Well, I used to play with all the Lucian Morgan and
Charles Ritchie.
See, Ritchie was Morgan.
I don't remember what he did.
But he had a house right where the Momoa Student Center is right now.
And when you were in high school, if you and your buddies were going to have a good time, did you all ever go out on a Saturday night and have a good time?
Where did you go?
I bought a bottle of tea.
And I fixed it up.
And the only real thing that we could find was on each end of the administration building, you know, the administration, the white one, there's some parking lots there.
Mm-hmm.
And they were the only ones big enough.
You take that Model T, and you just drive in there, and you kick that, just turn it as tight as you can.
Then you grab ahold of the ears and pull them down.
And you just sit there.
And it'll just go round and round and round and round like everybody that you know.
And I made a lot of friends with some of those.
And where did you take a date in those days?
Well, we took them to the dances at A&M.
Here at A&M?
How were the ladies treated at an A&M dance?
Well, you could go up and tap something.
No, I mean, were they treated nicely?
Oh, yes.
The boys behaved the way they... Oh, they were...
Boys were...
They were on their best behavior.
They were not... And how did everybody dress?
Oh, you had the best... You had your best... best clothes on.
And the women had full dresses on.
And the dances were held at Sabisa?
Sabisa?
Sabisa?
What were the big dances?
Which ones?
The ring dance, which it still is.
Do you remember going to the ring dance?
Yeah.
I imagine that's when, you know, that's just 30, I don't know, that was after that.
I probably, I don't know how I took that ring dance.
How much did your ring cost, do you remember?
Well, the problem I had
was that I was a small person.
When I entered A&M, I only weighed 105 pounds.
And so that big ring that they had, most of them wore, I just couldn't, it would just be like something heavy on my hand.
And that year they came out with what they call, I don't know what they call it, a sweetheart ring, but it was a ring for your date.
It was a woman's ring.
But it was the same design?
Exactly the same design.
And I bought one of those.
Put it on my finger and then it stayed there until my wife had to cut it off.
Do you remember what it cost?
Oh, it wasn't much money.
How did you feel when you first put that Aggie ring on?
Well, I was an Aggie long before that.
That was just a culmination of everything.
But you were proud.
You were proud of it.
You wouldn't do anything that didn't do it.
In all of the years that you've worn an Aggie ring...
Have you ever had any good ring stories?
Did you lose it and somebody found it?
No, we never did that.
The only thing I had to do was have my wife read it all.
Did you ever, were you ever in some place far, far away and somebody saw your Aggie ring?
No, I don't think so.
But...
We were talking about A's all the time.

Like one of my favorite ring stories, when I asked President Bowen for his ring story, he said that when he was a master's student at Caltech, he went to the University of Heidelberg for the summer in Germany.
And he said he and two of his German graduate student buddies are on the train going over the Brenner Pass in northern Italy on their way to Venice.
And they're over there having a good time.
And he said this very well-dressed lady is reading a paper.
She then lowers the paper and looks over it and suddenly says, oh, you're from Texas A&M?
Well, yes, ma'am.
How did you know?
Well, I saw your ring.
Well, how would you know an Aggie ring?
Well, my husband is an Aggie.
You might have heard of him.
His name is H.B.
Zachary.
And he said he told her, yes, ma'am, I've heard of him.
Well, I ran into Zachary.
See, I was on the electric board for the city of Brown for nine years.
See, the boys in the E department, they said, we want you on that board down there.
That was after I came back from World War II.
And so, uh, what happened was that, uh, it was Ward and, uh, what was the other guy's name?
They wanted me on that board.
And they got me on that board.
And I stayed there a while.
And then later on, uh, I ran it for, uh, nine years.
And, uh,
Of course, I came, I had worked for the REA prior to that.
So I was well immersed in all that, what they were doing.
And Brian was a part of the REA.
They had a, what we call a Texas public.
They had a REA.
You had a Texas public or you'd have a co-op.
They'd have a name.
But that's the salvation of our... Oh, yes.
You know why?
Why?
Because they amortize their loans.
Those co-ops sitting out there, they don't have enough.
The city of Bryan don't have a dime on those three big plants they got.
They're paid for.
That's 40% of your... See, in electric business, you got
40% for investments.
You got 40% as an additional 40% for fuel.
And 20% left for maintenance.
So you take 40% out of there, you got yourself, and that's what I think the deregulation ought to be.
And I hope the city of Bryan never does.
You bet.
Now you're A&M what class?
What year?
Did you know by chance when they were students, Earl Rudder or Tiger Teague?
Did you know them as students?
No, but when they were students, did you know them?
Yes.
Describe them as students.
What were they like?
Tiger Teague, he was always in business.
As a student?
Yeah.
What kind of business?
He took...
He had a closet in the dormitory over there, and you just take your clothes to him, and he'd take them to the cleaner, bring them back, and you'd pay him.
Now, he was a small man, wasn't he, as a student?
And he's called Tiger because he was so energetic?
No, I don't know anything about that.
I don't know that, but I do know that one of the things that happened to him, it was really, he had over there, I don't know where it was exactly.
It was somewhere in the Northgate area.
He had a room over there, and he took a lot of the,
the people that had disabilities.
This was long before we even had anything.
And so he brought them in there and he paid them a salary.
Now it wasn't the salary that he had to pay for by the government.
It was a good salary.
And they were doing a lot of stuff.
I don't know.
I think they were taking some clothing and reworking it or something.
It was a regular business.
This is while he was a student?
No.
Oh, after.
Immediately after.
This would be about...
In the late 30s?
Yeah.
What about Earl Rudder as a student?
Oh, I'm sorry.
And he had those people in there.
And the wage and hour people came in there.
And so they said, you've got to fire all those people because you can't pay them this wage.
And he says, I'm not going to fire them.
You go fire them.
He made that man go down there and tell those people that they didn't have any job anymore.
And that was the kind of man he was.
But he was a Democrat, sold out completely to the Democrat party.
And that's what bothered us.
Earl Rudder, did you know Earl as a student?
No, I never knew him as a student.
The only time I knew very much about him was I got on an airplane with him one day.
After World War II, after he's back here.
Yeah, and he was president there.
And we flew from here to, I think it was probably Kansas City.
We sat there in the front, the last seat before you got to the front, you know.
didn't have a seat in front of it.
We sat there and talked.
Back to your student days, you were not in the Corps as a senior, so you didn't have any senior boots.
No, I got a pair, but they weren't any good.
While you were an undergraduate, what were boys smoking in those days?
They smoked just regular cigarettes.
What kind?
What brand?
Campbell I never smoked.
I smoked a little until I went to Ames and got that to get my master's degree and I had that stipend up there.
And I didn't have enough money.
And so I quit because I couldn't pay for the cigarettes.
Back here when you were a student, were there many boys that smoked pipes or cigars?
No, most of them were cigarettes.
And did any of them roll their own?
Not those people, but we were in contact with a lot of people.
See, I traveled with Dad in the hardware association.
And, well, we met everybody.
So you saw people with Bull Durham and Prince Albert?
Oh, yeah.
What about snuff?
Did Aggies dip snuff then?
The Negro women dipped snuff.
The Negro women, they dipped snuff like it always was.
Did they put it in their lip or in their jaw?
In the lip.
It was always right here.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
Now, my son, he got involved in it, and he got it in his jaw.
Hmm.
And we had a hell of a time with that.
But what broke that up was that the, uh, he had, he had done, they had done some, what do you call it, orthotonic?
Big burn?
Uh, ortho, something for teeth.
Orthodontist?
Yeah.
Mm-hmm.
And they had done some work on his teeth.
And the, uh,
I said, I just told him that he had to stop because he would run his teeth.
And so he quit cold turkey.
Back to your A&M days, when you graduated, do you remember commencement?
What was it like?
What was the commencement ceremony like?
I think it was...
Was it in DeWare or Guyon Hall or out in the stadium?
It was in the stadium.
Well, it would be in probably Guyon Hall because there was only 300.
300 graduated?
Did every hand get shaken?
Every name was called?
Yes, it was.
It went across the stage.
Just like it is today.
How did you feel when you got your diploma?
Great.
I had a job with the USDA at that time, but it didn't last.
Did it not last because of the depression?
No, because of health.
I had appendicitis, for example.
I worked three weeks on it.
I was in
in the conservation service.
As you look back on your A&M undergraduate years, which teachers helped you the most?
The ones that you feel most grateful for having had as your teachers?
Well,
Well, old Cubone Ritchie, he was a good teacher.
He was a real good teacher.
And what did he teach?
Strength of Materials.
OK. Who else?
Oh, the guy in genetics.
I enjoyed that.
What was his name?
Do you remember?
I don't remember, but he had an aneurysm.
